When using fetch with a URL that does not return any body (i.e a delete route of an API) the following error is returned: 

```
Check file:///[...]/project/demo/empty_body.js
Provided input is not of type ArrayBuffer or ArrayBufferView
TypeError: Provided input is not of type ArrayBuffer or ArrayBufferView
    at TextDecoder.decode (/Users/runner/work/deno/deno/op_crates/web/08_text_encoding.js:456:15)
    at Response.text (rt/24_body.js:200:22)
    at async HttpRequests.request (http-requests.ts:50:34)
    at async HttpRequests.delete (http-requests.ts:163:12)
    at async Index.deleteIndex (index.ts:168:12)
    at async file:///[...]/project/demo/empty_body.js:14:1
```

Apparently the return body should be of either type `ArrayBuffer` or `ArrayBufferView`.
This error did not exists in previous versions.
I think it has to do with #7178

It does not expect the body to be `null` in `08_text_encoding.js:456:15`.

```javascript
 decode(
      input,
      options = { stream: false },
    ) {
      if (options.stream) {
        throw new TypeError("Stream not supported.");
      }

      let bytes;
      if (input instanceof Uint8Array) {
        bytes = input;
      } else if (isEitherArrayBuffer(input)) {
        bytes = new Uint8Array(input);
      } else if (
        typeof input === "object" &&
        input !== null &&
        "buffer" in input &&
        isEitherArrayBuffer(input.buffer)
      ) {
        bytes = new Uint8Array(
          input.buffer,
          input.byteOffset,
          input.byteLength,
        );
      } else {
        throw new TypeError(
          "Provided input is not of type ArrayBuffer or ArrayBufferView",
        );
      }
```

So my question is: 
Is this a problem with fetch, a problem with this function or a bad practice to not return a body?

## Reproduction
main.js:
```
import * as path from "https://deno.land/std@0.67.0/path/mod.ts";
const { a, ...rest } = { a: 3, b: "bar" };
console.log(a, rest);
```
CLI:
```
deno bundle main.js build/main.js
deno run build/main.js
```
results in:

> error: Uncaught ReferenceError: __rest is not defined
            _a = { a: 3, b: "bar" }, a = _a.a, rest = __rest(_a, ["a"]);
                                       ^
    at execute (file:///tmp/TestProj/build/main.js:389:40)
    at gExp (file:///tmp/TestProj/build/main.js:90:7)
    at __instantiate (file:///tmp/TestProj/build/main.js:97:27)
    at file:///tmp/TestProj/build/main.js:395:1

build/main.js emits:
```
System.register("file:///tmp/TestProj/main", [], function (exports_11, context_11) {
    // ...
    return {
        // ...
        execute: function () {
            _a = { a: 3, b: "bar" }, a = _a.a, rest = __rest(_a, ["a"]); // this is the error cause
            // ...
        }
    };
});
```
The `__rest` method is not defined anywhere in the emitted build output.

If I comment out the `import` statement on first line, it works again. `deno bundle` seems to change its build output conditionally dependent on whether the file is a script or a module - doesn't matter what exactly is imported.

Is this a `deno bundle` error or could it be more related to underlying TS SystemJS bundling?

