```

Happy to put in a small PR 🙃

In all browser vendors and Node.js, when using `console.log` on an object containing getters, the getters are shown as getters, they aren't actually called.

Example:
```ts
let i = 0n;

const objectContainingGetter = {
	get x() {
		return ++i;
	}
};

console.log(objectContainingGetter);
// expected to be something along the lines of
// { [x: getter] }

console.log(objectContainingGetter.x);
// expected to be "1n"
```

TypeScript 4.0 supports optional named tuple types, even with #6514 Deno does not support this feature.

For example the following as an input file:

```ts
function foo(x: [first: string, second?: number]) {
  const [a, b] = x;
  console.log(a, b);
}

foo(["ao", 1]);
```

Will result in something like:

```
error: Expected Comma, got Some(Colon) at file:///optional_named_tuples.ts:1:39
```

This is upstream in swc and being worked on.

Ref: swc-project/swc#978

cc/ @dsherret

